allery>\nFile:John Galbraith Graham.jpg|[[John Galbraith Graham]], best known as crossword compiler Araucaria, chaplain and tutor 1949-1952.\nFile:Michael Ramsey 1974.jpg|[[Michael Ramsey]], the 100th [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], resident fellow and governor\nFile:Maeve Sherlock.jpg|[[Maeve Sherlock|Baroness Sherlock of Durham]] OBE, honorary fellow\n</gallery>{{Col-begin}}\n* [[John Galbraith Graham]] MBE, noted British crossword puzzle compiler \u2013 'Araucaria' of [[the Guardian]]\n* [[Giles Ramsay]] \u2013  theatre director, producer and playwright, Fellow<ref>[\"Fellows\". St Chad's College. Retrieved 5 April 2009. \"Fellows\"]. St Chad's College. Retrieved 2009-04-05.</ref>\n* [[Michael Ramsey]] (Baron Ramsey of Canterbury) PC \u2013 former College Tutor, Fellow, Governor and Visitor, [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] (1961\u20131974)\n* [[Maeve Sherlock]] (Baroness Sherlock of Durham) OBE, awarded life peerage in May 2010, Honorary Fellow, former Chief executive of the [[Refugee Council]] and policy advisor to [[Gordon Brown]]\n* [[David Stancliffe]], Fellow, retired Bishop of [[Salisbury]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category}}\n* [[Chad of Mercia]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dur.ac.uk/StChads St Chad's College official website]\n\n{{University of Durham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Chad's College}}\n[[Category:1904 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Colleges of Durham University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1904]]\n[[Category:Former theological colleges in England]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in County Durham]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed educational buildings]]\n[[Category:St Chad's College, Durham| ]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther notable associated people:ital", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Chad%27s_College,_Durham"}
{"title_page": "St Pancras, London", "text_new": "{{short description|Area of central London, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Other uses|St. Pancras (disambiguation){{!}}St. Pancras}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2017}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|map_type                 = Greater London\n|region                   = London\n|population               =\n|official_name            = St Pancras\n|static_image_name        = British Library + St Pancras 7527-31hug.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 300px\n|static_image_caption     = The [[British Library]], [[St Pancras railway station|the railway station]] and [[Euston Road]] seen in 2009\n|coordinates              = {{coord|51.5262|-0.1178|display=inline,title}}\n|london_borough           = Camden\n|constituency_westminster = [[Holborn and St. Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]]\n|post_town                = LONDON\n|postcode_district        = WC1\n|postcode_area            = WC \n|postcode_district1       = NW1\n|postcode_area1           = NW  \n|dial_code                = 020\n|os_grid_reference        = TQ305825\n}}\n\n'''St Pancras''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u00e6|\u014b|k|r|\u0259|s}}) is an area of [[Central London|Central]] and [[North London|North West]] [[London]]. For many centuries the name was used for various officially designated areas, but it is now used mainly for the [[St Pancras railway station|railway station]] and for upmarket venues in the immediate locality, having been largely superseded by other place names including [[Kings Cross, London|Kings Cross]] and [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]].\n\n==History==\n===Medieval parish===\n[[File:St Pancras Met. B Ward Map 1916.svg|thumb|A map showing the wards of St Pancras Metropolitan Borough as they appeared in 1916.]]\nThe [[Civil Parish#Ancient parishes|Ancient Parish]] of St Pancras (also known as Pancrace or Pancridge<ref name=\"Chalfant2008\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPLExnmXvCYC&pg=PA136|title=Ben Jonson's London: A Jacobean Placename Dictionary|author=Fran C. Chalfant|date=1 July 2008|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-3291-8|pages=136\u2013}}</ref>) was established in the medieval period to serve four manors; Pancras (named after the dedication of the parish church), [[Kentish Town]], [[Tottenham Court Road#Manor of Tottenham Court|Tottenham Court]] and Rugmere.<ref>BHO - used  to support the four manors making up St Pancras https://www.british-history.ac.uk/old-new-london/vol5/pp324-340</ref>\n\nThe district now encompassed by the term \"St Pancras\" is not easy to define, and its usage as a place name is fairly limited. The name is sometimes applied to the immediate vicinity of the eponymous railway station, but King's Cross is the usual name for the area around the two mainline stations as a whole.\n\n[[File:LONDON, MARYLEBONE by BARTLETT, F.A. and B.J. DAVIES.jpg|260px|thumb|The [[Civil Parish#Ancient Parishes|Ancient Parishes]] of - west to east - [[Paddington]] and [[Marylebone|St Marylebone]] (in the modern [[City of Westminster]]), and St Pancras (in the modern [[London Borough of Camden]]). 1834.]]\nSt Pancras was originally a medieval [[parish]], which ran from close to what is now [[Oxford Street]] north as far as [[Highgate]], and from what is now [[Regent's Park]] in the west to the road now known as [[York Way]] in the east, boundaries which take in much of the current [[London Borough of Camden]], including its central part. \n\n[[File:St Pancras Old Church 2005.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Old St Pancras Parish Church.]]\n\nThe original focus of the area was the church, now known by the [[retronym]] of [[St Pancras Old Church]]. In the Middle Ages had \"disreputable associations\",<ref name=\"Chalfant20082\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPLExnmXvCYC&pg=PA136|title=Ben Jonson's London: A Jacobean Placename Dictionary|author=Fran C. Chalfant|date=1 July 2008|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-3291-8|pages=136\u2013}}</ref> and by the 17th century had become the \"'[[Gretna Green]]' of the London area\".<ref name=\"Chalfant20082\" />  [[English Renaissance theatre|Elizabethan playwright]] [[Ben Jonson]] alludes, on that account, to the area frequently in his plays.<ref name=\"Chalfant20082\" />{{Refn|This is the foundation for the expression \"[[Pancridge Parson]]\", i.e. a minister who will \"perform suden or irregular marriages\".<ref name=\"Chalfant2008\" />|group=}} The building is in the southern half of the parish, and is believed by many to be one of [[History of Christianity in Britain|the oldest sites of Christian worship in Great Britain]]. However, in the 14th century the population moved ''en masse'' to [[Kentish Town]], probably due to flooding by the [[River Fleet]] and the availability of better wells at the new location. A [[chapel of ease]] was established there, and the old settlement was abandoned, except for a few farms, until the growth of London in the late eighteenth century.\n\nIn the 1790s [[Earl Camden]] began to develop some fields to the north and west of the old church as [[Camden Town]].<ref>Camden Town and Primrose Hill Past by John Richardson (1991) {{ISBN|0-948667-12-5}}</ref> About the same time, a residential district was built to the south and east of the church, usually known as [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]]. In 1822 the [[St Pancras New Church|new church of St Pancras]] was dedicated as the [[parish church]]. The site was chosen on what was then called the New Road, now [[Euston Road]], which had been built as London's first bypass, the [[M25 motorway|M25]] of its day. The two sites are about a kilometer apart. The new church is [[Grade I listed]] for its [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival style]]; the old church [[Victorian restoration|was rebuilt]] in 1847. In the mid 19th century two major railway stations were built to the south of the Old Church, first [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]] and later [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras]]. The new church is closer to [[Euston railway station|Euston station]].\n\nBy the end of the nineteenth century the ancient parish had been divided into 37 parishes, including one for the old church. There are currently 17 [[Church of England]] parishes completely contained within the boundaries of the ancient parish, all of which benefit from the distributions from the St Pancras Lands Trust, and most of which are in South Camden Deanery in the [[Bishop of Edmonton (London)|Edmonton Area]] of the [[Diocese of London]].\n\n===Metropolitan borough===\nThe parish of St Pancras was administered by a [[vestry]] until the [[Metropolitan Borough of St Pancras]] was established in 1900. In 1965 the former area of the borough was combined with that of two others to form the [[London Borough of Camden]].\n\nIn the 1950s, St Pancras Council gained a reputation for left-wing radicalism, being referred to as \"the most freakish borough in London.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=86}}</ref>  The council refused to take part in [[civil defence]] preparations for war, which local councils were obliged to provide.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=110}}</ref>  John Lawrence as Mayor was monitored by the Home Office and, as of 2016, the Home Office still refuses Freedom of Information requests relating to Lawrence on the grounds of protecting national security.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=215}}</ref> \n\nHousing was in [[excess demand]] after the damage and disruption of the [[Second World War]].  There was strong opposition to the [[History_of_rent_control_in_England_and_Wales#Decontrol_1957_to_1965|1957 Rent Act]], which led to a series of decisions that caused serious financial difficulty.  John Lawrence and several other councillors were expelled from the Labour Party in 1958, but continued to serve as the Independent Socialists.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=154}}</ref>  The Conservative Party won the 1958 council election.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=158}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, there was a widespread rent strike in the district, which led to rioting in September.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=180}}</ref>\n\n==Cemeteries==\n[[File:2780theHardyTreeOldStPancrasChurchyard.jpg|thumb|The Hardy Tree, growing between gravestones moved while [[Thomas Hardy]] was working here]]\n\nDuring the 18th and 19th centuries, St Pancras was famous for its cemeteries: as well as the graveyard of Old St Pancras Church, it also contained the cemeteries of [[St James's Church, Piccadilly]], [[St Giles in the Fields]], [[St Andrew, Holborn]], [[St. George's Church, Bloomsbury]], and [[St George the Martyr Holborn|St George the Martyr, Holborn]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/MDX/StPancras/StPancrasHistory |title=St. Pancras |last=Hinson |first=Colin |year=2003 |website=GENUKI: UK & Ireland Genealogy |access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref> These were all closed under the [[Extramural Interment Act 1854|Extramural Interment Act]] in 1854; the parish was required to purchase land some distance away, and chose [[East Finchley]] for its new [[St Pancras Cemetery]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://stpancras.com/history |title=History |website=St Pancras International |publisher=HS1 Ltd |access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe disused graveyard at St Pancras Old Church was left alone for over thirty years, until the building of the [[Midland Railway]] required the removal of many of the graves. [[Thomas Hardy]], then a junior architect and later a novelist and poet, was involved in this work. Particularly, he placed a number of gravestones around a tree, now known as \"the Hardy Tree\".<ref name=\"vweb\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.victorianweb.org/photos/hardy/74.html |title=The Hardy Tree, St Pancras Churchyard, London |date=2006-04-17 |website=The Victorian Web |access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref> The cemetery was disturbed again in 2002\u201303 by the construction of the [[Channel Tunnel Rail Link]], but much more care was given to the removal of remains than in the 19th century.\n\n==Political divisions==\nThe name St Pancras survives in the name of the local parliamentary [[constituency]], [[Holborn and St. Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St. Pancras]]. One of the political [[Ward (subnational entity)|wards]] in Camden is called St Pancras and Somers Town; however, ward boundaries are chosen to divide a borough into roughly equal slices with little regard to historical boundaries or day-to-day usage. Besides Somers Town and the area around St Pancras Old Church, the ward includes much of Camden Town and the former Kings Cross Goods Yard, which is being redeveloped as a mixed-use district under the name [[Kings Cross Central]].\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Haringay Camden boundary.jpg|thumb|upright|Boundary stone between St Pancras and [[Hornsey]] at [[Highgate]]]]\nOld St Pancras Church and its graveyard have links to [[Charles Dickens]], [[Thomas Hardy]], and the [[Mary Wollstonecraft|Wollstonecraft]] circle.<ref name=\"vweb\" /> Immediately to the north of the churchyard is [[St Pancras Hospital]], originally the parish [[workhouse]] and latterly the [[London Hospital for Tropical Diseases]]. St Pancras is one of the best-known [[railway station]]s in England. It has been extended and is now the terminus for the [[Eurostar]] services through the [[Channel Tunnel]].\n\n===Transport===\n;Nearest places\n* [[King's Cross, London|King's Cross]] and [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]] to the north \n* [[Bloomsbury]] to the west and south\n* [[Clerkenwell]] to the east\n\nThe nearest [[London Underground]] stations are [[King's Cross St Pancras tube station|King's Cross St Pancras]] and [[Russell Square tube station|Russell Square]]. The nearest [[National Rail]] stations are [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] and [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras]].\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[Monica Charlot]], historian\n* [[Elizabeth Eiloart]], writer\n* [[Reg Freeson]], politician\n* [[William Hartnell]], actor\n* [[Barnaby Kay]], actor\n* [[Andrew Lincoln]], actor\n* [[W. B. Yeats]], poet\n* [[John William Fisher Beaumont]], justice\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{LB Camden}}{{Areas of London}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Pancras}}\n[[Category:St Pancras, London| ]]\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Camden]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Area of central London, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Other uses|St. Pancras (disambiguation){{!}}St. Pancras}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2017}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|map_type                 = Greater London\n|region                   = London\n|population               =\n|official_name            = St Pancras\n|static_image_name        = British Library + St Pancras 7527-31hug.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 300px\n|static_image_caption     = The [[British Library]], [[St Pancras railway station|the railway station]] and [[Euston Road]] seen in 2009\n|coordinates              = {{coord|51.5262|-0.1178|display=inline,title}}\n|london_borough           = Camden\n|constituency_westminster = [[Holborn and St. Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]]\n|post_town                = LONDON\n|postcode_district        = WC1\n|postcode_area            = WC \n|postcode_district1       = NW1\n|postcode_area1           = NW  \n|dial_code                = 020\n|os_grid_reference        = TQ305825\n}}\n\n'''St Pancras''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u00e6|\u014b|k|r|\u0259|s}}) is an area of [[Central London|Central]] and [[North London|North West]] [[London]]. For many centuries the name was used for various officially designated areas, but it is now used mainly for the [[St Pancras railway station|railway station]] and for upmarket venues in the immediate locality, having been largely superseded by other place names including [[Kings Cross, London|Kings Cross]] and [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]].\n\n==History==\n===Medieval parish===\n[[File:St Pancras Met. B Ward Map 1916.svg|thumb|A map showing the wards of St Pancras Metropolitan Borough as they appeared in 1916.]]\nThe [[Civil Parish#Ancient parishes|Ancient Parish]] of St Pancras (also known as Pancrace or Pancridge<ref name=\"Chalfant2008\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPLExnmXvCYC&pg=PA136|title=Ben Jonson's London: A Jacobean Placename Dictionary|author=Fran C. Chalfant|date=1 July 2008|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-3291-8|pages=136\u2013}}</ref>) was established in the medieval period to serve four manors; Pancras (named after the dedication of the parish church), [[Kentish Town]], [[Tottenham Court Road#Manor of Tottenham Court|Tottenham Court]] and Rugmere.<ref>BHO - used  to support the four manors making up St Pancras https://www.british-history.ac.uk/old-new-london/vol5/pp324-340</ref>\n\nThe district now encompassed by the term \"St Pancras\" is not easy to define, and its usage as a place name is fairly limited. The name is sometimes applied to the immediate vicinity of the eponymous railway station, but King's Cross is the usual name for the area around the two mainline stations as a whole.\n\n[[File:LONDON, MARYLEBONE by BARTLETT, F.A. and B.J. DAVIES.jpg|260px|thumb|The [[Civil Parish#Ancient Parishes|Ancient Parishes]] of - west to east - [[Paddington]] and [[Marylebone|St Marylebone]] (in the modern [[City of Westminster]]), and St Pancras (in the modern [[London Borough of Camden]]). 1834.]]\nSt Pancras was originally a medieval [[parish]], which ran from close to what is now [[Oxford Street]] north as far as [[Highgate]], and from what is now [[Regent's Park]] in the west to the road now known as [[York Way]] in the east, boundaries which take in much of the current [[London Borough of Camden]], including its central part. \n\n[[File:St Pancras Old Church 2005.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Old St Pancras Parish Church.]]\n\nThe original focus of the area was the church, now known by the [[retronym]] of [[St Pancras Old Church]]. In the Middle Ages had \"disreputable associations\",<ref name=\"Chalfant20082\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPLExnmXvCYC&pg=PA136|title=Ben Jonson's London: A Jacobean Placename Dictionary|author=Fran C. Chalfant|date=1 July 2008|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-3291-8|pages=136\u2013}}</ref> and by the 17th century had become the \"'[[Gretna Green]]' of the London area\".<ref name=\"Chalfant20082\" />  [[English Renaissance theatre|Elizabethan playwright]] [[Ben Jonson]] alludes, on that account, to the area frequently in his plays.<ref name=\"Chalfant20082\" />{{Refn|This is the foundation for the expression \"[[Pancridge Parson]]\", i.e. a minister who will \"perform suden or irregular marriages\".<ref name=\"Chalfant2008\">{{cite book|author=Fran C. Chalfant|title=Ben Jonson's London: A Jacobean Placename Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPLExnmXvCYC&pg=PA136|date=1 July 2008|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-3291-8|pages=136\u2013}}</ref>|group=}} The building is in the southern half of the parish, and is believed by many to be one of [[History of Christianity in Britain|the oldest sites of Christian worship in Great Britain]]. However, in the 14th century the population moved ''en masse'' to [[Kentish Town]], probably due to flooding by the [[River Fleet]] and the availability of better wells at the new location. A [[chapel of ease]] was established there, and the old settlement was abandoned, except for a few farms, until the growth of London in the late eighteenth century.\n\nIn the 1790s [[Earl Camden]] began to develop some fields to the north and west of the old church as [[Camden Town]].<ref>Camden Town and Primrose Hill Past by John Richardson (1991) {{ISBN|0-948667-12-5}}</ref> About the same time, a residential district was built to the south and east of the church, usually known as [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]]. In 1822 the [[St Pancras New Church|new church of St Pancras]] was dedicated as the [[parish church]]. The site was chosen on what was then called the New Road, now [[Euston Road]], which had been built as London's first bypass, the [[M25 motorway|M25]] of its day. The two sites are about a kilometer apart. The new church is [[Grade I listed]] for its [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival style]]; the old church [[Victorian restoration|was rebuilt]] in 1847. In the mid 19th century two major railway stations were built to the south of the Old Church, first [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]] and later [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras]]. The new church is closer to [[Euston railway station|Euston station]].\n\nBy the end of the nineteenth century the ancient parish had been divided into 37 parishes, including one for the old church. There are currently 17 [[Church of England]] parishes completely contained within the boundaries of the ancient parish, all of which benefit from the distributions from the St Pancras Lands Trust, and most of which are in South Camden Deanery in the [[Bishop of Edmonton (London)|Edmonton Area]] of the [[Diocese of London]].\n\n===Metropolitan borough===\nThe parish of St Pancras was administered by a [[vestry]] until the [[Metropolitan Borough of St Pancras]] was established in 1900. In 1965 the former area of the borough was combined with that of two others to form the [[London Borough of Camden]].\n\nIn the 1950s, St Pancras Council gained a reputation for left-wing radicalism, being referred to as \"the most freakish borough in London.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=86}}</ref>  The council refused to take part in [[civil defence]] preparations for war, which local councils were obliged to provide.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=110}}</ref>  John Lawrence as Mayor was monitored by the Home Office and, as of 2016, the Home Office still refuses Freedom of Information requests relating to Lawrence on the grounds of protecting national security.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=215}}</ref> \n\nHousing was in [[excess demand]] after the damage and disruption of the [[Second World War]].  There was strong opposition to the [[History_of_rent_control_in_England_and_Wales#Decontrol_1957_to_1965|1957 Rent Act]], which led to a series of decisions that caused serious financial difficulty.  John Lawrence and several other councillors were expelled from the Labour Party in 1958, but continued to serve as the Independent Socialists.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=154}}</ref>  The Conservative Party won the 1958 council election.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=158}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, there was a widespread rent strike in the district, which led to rioting in September.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mathieson |first=David |date=2016 |title=Radical London in the 1950s |location=Stroud, UK |publisher=Amberley |isbn=9781445661032|page=180}}</ref>\n\n==Cemeteries==\n[[File:2780theHardyTreeOldStPancrasChurchyard.jpg|thumb|The Hardy Tree, growing between gravestones moved while [[Thomas Hardy]] was working here]]\n\nDuring the 18th and 19th centuries, St Pancras was famous for its cemeteries: as well as the graveyard of Old St Pancras Church, it also contained the cemeteries of [[St James's Church, Piccadilly]], [[St Giles in the Fields]], [[St Andrew, Holborn]], [[St. George's Church, Bloomsbury]], and [[St George the Martyr Holborn|St George the Martyr, Holborn]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/MDX/StPancras/StPancrasHistory |title=St. Pancras |last=Hinson |first=Colin |year=2003 |website=GENUKI: UK & Ireland Genealogy |access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref> These were all closed under the [[Extramural Interment Act 1854|Extramural Interment Act]] in 1854; the parish was required to purchase land some distance away, and chose [[East Finchley]] for its new [[St Pancras Cemetery]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://stpancras.com/history |title=History |website=St Pancras International |publisher=HS1 Ltd |access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe disused graveyard at St Pancras Old Church was left alone for over thirty years, until the building of the [[Midland Railway]] required the removal of many of the graves. [[Thomas Hardy]], then a junior architect and later a novelist and poet, was involved in this work. Particularly, he placed a number of gravestones around a tree, now known as \"the Hardy Tree\".<ref name=\"vweb\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.victorianweb.org/photos/hardy/74.html |title=The Hardy Tree, St Pancras Churchyard, London |date=2006-04-17 |website=The Victorian Web |access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref> The cemetery was disturbed again in 2002\u201303 by the construction of the [[Channel Tunnel Rail Link]], but much more care was given to the removal of remains than in the 19th century.\n\n==Political divisions==\nThe name St Pancras survives in the name of the local parliamentary [[constituency]], [[Holborn and St. Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St. Pancras]]. One of the political [[Ward (subnational entity)|wards]] in Camden is called St Pancras and Somers Town; however, ward boundaries are chosen to divide a borough into roughly equal slices with little regard to historical boundaries or day-to-day usage. Besides Somers Town and the area around St Pancras Old Church, the ward includes much of Camden Town and the former Kings Cross Goods Yard, which is being redeveloped as a mixed-use district under the name [[Kings Cross Central]].\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Haringay Camden boundary.jpg|thumb|upright|Boundary stone between St Pancras and [[Hornsey]] at [[Highgate]]]]\nOld St Pancras Church and its graveyard have links to [[Charles Dickens]], [[Thomas Hardy]], and the [[Mary Wollstonecraft|Wollstonecraft]] circle.<ref name=\"vweb\" /> Immediately to the north of the churchyard is [[St Pancras Hospital]], originally the parish [[workhouse]] and latterly the [[London Hospital for Tropical Diseases]]. St Pancras is one of the best-known [[railway station]]s in England. It has been extended and is now the terminus for the [[Eurostar]] services through the [[Channel Tunnel]].\n\n===Transport===\n;Nearest places\n* [[King's Cross, London|King's Cross]] and [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]] to the north \n* [[Bloomsbury]] to the west and south\n* [[Clerkenwell]] to the east\n\nThe nearest [[London Underground]] stations are [[King's Cross St Pancras tube station|King's Cross St Pancras]] and [[Russell Square tube station|Russell Square]]. The nearest [[National Rail]] stations are [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] and [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras]].\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[Monica Charlot]], historian\n* [[Elizabeth Eiloart]], writer\n* [[Reg Freeson]], politician\n* [[William Hartnell]], actor\n* [[Barnaby Kay]], actor\n* [[Andrew Lincoln]], actor\n* [[W. B. Yeats]], poet\n* [[John William Fisher Beaumont]], justice\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{LB Camden}}{{Areas of London}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Pancras}}\n[[Category:St Pancras, London| ]]\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Camden]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Pancras,_London"}
{"title_page": "Madan Singh Chouhan", "text_new": "'''Madan Singh Chauhan''' (born 15 October, 1947) also known as \"Guruji\" is a Folk & Sufi Singer from [[Raipur]], [[Chhattisgarh]], India. In 2020,he received the [[Padma Shri]] honour from the [[Government of India]] for his contribution in the field of Art.<ref name=\"dailypioneer\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/state-editions/madan-singh-chouhan-to-be-conferred-padma-shri.html|title=Madan Singh Chouhan to be conferred Padma Shri|website=dailypioneer|language=en|date=|access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"khabartak\">{{cite news|url=https://khabartak.com/awards/madan-singh/|title=\u091b\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0940\u0938\u0917\u0922\u093c \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u094b\u0915\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u0938\u0902\u0917\u0940\u0924\u0915\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0926\u0928 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u091a\u094c\u0939\u093e\u0928 \u0915\u094b \u092a\u0926\u094d\u092e\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u200d\u092e\u093e\u0928|website=KhabarTak.com|language=hi|date=|access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bhaskar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/chhattisgarh/raipur/news/state-musician-madan-singh-chauhan-selected-for-padma-shri-126603610.html|title=\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f \u0915\u0947 \u0938\u0902\u0917\u0940\u0924\u0915\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0926\u0928 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u091a\u094c\u0939\u093e\u0928 \u0915\u094b \u092a\u0926\u094d\u092e\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940, \u092e\u0941\u0916\u094d\u092f\u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u092d\u0942\u092a\u0947\u0936 \u092c\u0918\u0947\u0932 \u0928\u0947 \u0926\u0940 \u092c\u0927\u093e\u0908|website=Bhaskar|language=hi|date=|access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nGuruji devoted his entire life to music practice, He Started his career with Dholak and then he spent 30 years in a tabla.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Padma Shri Award]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padm